docs.abstract: Two reports commissioned by the Senate Intelligence Committee take a deeper look at the fake social media accounts used by Russia in the American election.
docs.snippet: Two reports commissioned by the Senate Intelligence Committee take a deeper look at the fake social media accounts used by Russia in the American election.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Russian influence campaign on social media in the 2016 election made an extraordinary effort to target African-Americans, used an array of tactics to try to suppress turnout among Democratic voters and unleashed a blizzard of activity on Instagram that rivaled or exceeded its posts on Facebook, according to a report produced for the Senate Intelligence Committee.

headline.main: Russian 2016 Influence Operation Targeted African-Americans on Social Media

docs.lead_paragraph: The 24 Hour Plays move fast. That’s been their nature since their first production in 1995: short plays written, rehearsed and performed onstage in a scant 24-hour span. And when the pandemic shuttered theaters, the 24 Hour Plays responded with astonishing alacrity.

headline.main: Instant Artifacts of a Disconnected Time (and Lots of Hugh Dancy)

docs.abstract: The first African American woman to win the Pulitzer Prize in drama has four shows this season. “If you can hear the world singing, it’s your job to write it down,” she said.
docs.snippet: The first African American woman to win the Pulitzer Prize in drama has four shows this season. “If you can hear the world singing, it’s your job to write it down,” she said.
docs.lead_paragraph: Suzan-Lori Parks is drawn to archways. Early on in her New York life, long before she became one of the nation’s most acclaimed playwrights, she lived above a McDonald’s on Sixth Avenue — the Golden Arches. Then she moved out by Brooklyn’s Grand Army Plaza, with its triumphal Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Arch. Now she lives in an apartment overlooking the marble monument honoring the nation’s first president at the entrance to Washington Square Park.

headline.main: Suzan-Lori Parks Is on Broadway, Off Broadway and Everywhere Else
headline.print_headline: Plenty of Her Worlds on View

docs.abstract: Eight short plays take cues from the 1930 Noël Coward comedy — but now the stakes are different.
docs.snippet: Eight short plays take cues from the 1930 Noël Coward comedy — but now the stakes are different.
docs.lead_paragraph: An unlikely hodgepodge of names gets dropped in the course of Red Bull Theater’s Short New Play Festival: Virginia Woolf, Rachel Dolezal, Troilus, Cressida, Cervantes, Trump. But the name that gets dropped hardest — dropped in the sense that it all but disappears — is that of the production’s touchstone, Noël Coward.

headline.main: Review: Reliving ‘Private Lives,’ This Time Mostly Women’s
headline.print_headline: Short Plays That Take Their Cue From Coward

docs.abstract: Video footage of the fatal encounter included critical moments in which police officers kicked, punched and pepper-sprayed Mr. Nichols, 29, while he screamed.
docs.snippet: Video footage of the fatal encounter included critical moments in which police officers kicked, punched and pepper-sprayed Mr. Nichols, 29, while he screamed.
docs.lead_paragraph: MEMPHIS — The police officers kicked Tyre Nichols in the head, pepper-sprayed him and hit him repeatedly with a baton, even as he showed no signs of fighting back. At one point, after Mr. Nichols stood up, one officer struck him with at least five forceful blows while another held Mr. Nichols’s hands behind his back.

headline.main: Tyre Nichols Cried in Anguish. Memphis Officers Kept Hitting.
